PCI: vmd: Add support for the second (PCH) VMD rootbus on Intel Arrow Lake

On Arrow Lake desktop platforms (Core Ultra 200S), NVMe drives attached
through the PCH sit on a second VMD rootbus hardwired to bus 0x80. The
mainline vmd driver only enumerates the first rootbus, so those drives
are invisible to FOS and imaging fails with "no disks found" (FOGProject
issue #107).

Intel's fix ("PCI: vmd: Add support for second rootbus under VMD",
Szymon Durawa) is still unmerged upstream as of v5 (2026-06-25). Ubuntu
ships it as SAUCE patches in linux-oem-6.11 (Launchpad bug #2085853).
This is those four patches combined and adapted to vanilla 6.12.35:

  0c9ff92b2efc UBUNTU: SAUCE: PCI: vmd: Clean up vmd_enable_domain function
  d20355bdd463 UBUNTU: SAUCE: PCI: vmd: Add VMD PCH rootbus support
  e7b7195e3706 UBUNTU: SAUCE: PCI: vmd: Add WA for VMD PCH rootbus support
  040d304c75b9 UBUNTU: SAUCE: PCI: vmd: Fix use-after-free bug in resource
               name assignment

Adaptation: dropped the pci_lock_rescan_remove()/pci_unlock_rescan_remove()
calls in vmd_enable_domain, which exist only in Ubuntu's 6.11 tree, and
Ubuntu's aspm_os_control field which mainline lacks. Everything else is
verbatim. Remove this patch once the upstream series lands in the stable
kernel FOS builds from.

